Intuition
So for this problem my intuition was this can be solved using slow and fast pointer pattern and for that i use 2 pointers slow and fast , slow pointer moves by 1 node at a time and fast pointer moves faster than slow pointer suppose 2 nodes at a time , and normally if it is a straight linked list then they would never meet and fast poointer will reach final node address which will be none , but if these pointers meet at any point then for sure there is a cycle .

Approach
slow and fast pointer at head
loop condition while fast and fast.next :
move slow pointer
move fast pointer
If a cycle exists, the fast pointer moves faster than the slow pointer and will eventually catch up to it inside the cycle. If no cycle exists, the fast pointer will reach None.

if slow == fast:
    cycle exists return True
if loop ends there is no cycle return False

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Space complexity:
O(1)
Code
# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, x):
#         self.val = x
#         self.next = None

class Solution:
    def hasCycle(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> bool:
        slow = head
        fast = head
        while fast != None and fast.next != None:
            slow = slow.next
            fast = fast.next.next
            if slow == fast:
                return True
        return False
